Smith:
To battle these rising
carbon dioxide levels,

06:11.125 --> 06:13.375
groundbreaking technologies
are being developed

06:13.458 --> 06:15.709
to cool down the Earth
and slow sea-level rise

06:15.792 --> 06:17.709
by removing carbon
from the atmosphere,

06:17.792 --> 06:19.417
brightening clouds,

06:19.500 --> 06:22.041
and even replicating
volcanic eruptions

06:22.125 --> 06:24.583
to reflect sunlight
away from the planet.

06:26.125 --> 06:28.041
And in one experimental
site in the Arctic,

06:28.125 --> 06:31.709
a scientific team
is focusing their work
on the ice itself.

06:31.792 --> 06:36.125
So we sent Ben Anderson
to Alaska's
northern-most town.

06:43.959 --> 06:46.208
Leslie Field:
This is hollow glass
microspheres.

06:46.291 --> 06:48.917
You can think of it as
a form of floating sand.

06:49.000 --> 06:50.375
It's reflective, it's bright.

06:50.458 --> 06:54.000
It's basically
a thin, silica shell

06:54.083 --> 06:56.208
around a gas core.

06:56.291 --> 06:59.250
I mean, a lot of these things,
seem to be about
damage limitation.

06:59.333 --> 07:01.250
-But this is actually
about boosting--
-Yeah, we're--

07:01.333 --> 07:04.041
We're working
on Arctic restoration.

07:04.125 --> 07:08.250
People are attributing
a quarter to a half of
global temperature rise

07:08.333 --> 07:10.208
every year, right now,

07:10.291 --> 07:13.917
is coming from the loss
of that reflective heat shield
in the Arctic.

07:14.000 --> 07:16.917
We-- we want to build that back
to be the Earth's heat shield,

07:17.000 --> 07:18.500
the Earth's refrigerator.

07:26.500 --> 07:28.750
Smith:
The idea is
surprisingly simple:

07:28.834 --> 07:30.709
cover the ice
with reflective sand

07:30.792 --> 07:33.083
to reduce the amount
of sunlight absorbed.

07:33.166 --> 07:36.083
The team is testing
the concept
on a small scale

07:36.166 --> 07:38.125
on a nearby frozen lake.

07:40.417 --> 07:43.291
(wind blowing)

