12:48.041 --> 12:50.750
and their abilities to
actually darken our skies

12:50.834 --> 12:53.333
and thereby cool the planet.

12:56.208 --> 12:58.583
At one of the most
active volcanoes on Earth,

12:58.667 --> 13:00.583
Guatemala's Volcán de Fuego,

13:00.667 --> 13:03.250
scientists are studying
how ash cloud particles

13:03.333 --> 13:05.250
can effect
global temperatures.

13:05.333 --> 13:07.917
So we visited with
volcanologist Matt Watson,

13:08.000 --> 13:10.792
during the months
before its devastating
eruption this summer

13:10.875 --> 13:13.291
which killed more
than 160 people.

13:13.375 --> 13:15.583
(indistinct shouting)

13:15.667 --> 13:18.500
In 1991,
Mount Pinatubo erupted.

13:18.583 --> 13:21.291
It was the largest eruption
of the 20th century,

13:21.375 --> 13:23.625
and it had a profound
impact on climate.

13:23.709 --> 13:26.125
We saw a drop in temperature
around about half a degree.

13:26.208 --> 13:28.834
We see a drop
in global temperature

13:28.917 --> 13:30.917
after large eruptions,

13:31.000 --> 13:33.959
and that-- that's because
sulfur dioxide is ejected

13:34.041 --> 13:36.125
by volcanoes
into the atmosphere,

13:36.208 --> 13:38.500
that converts into
sulfate aerosol,

13:38.583 --> 13:39.959
which act like
tiny, little mirrors,

13:40.041 --> 13:42.500
and scatter incoming
solar radiation

13:42.583 --> 13:43.959
back out into space.

13:44.041 --> 13:46.291
That has the effect
of cooling the planet.

13:46.375 --> 13:48.458
I'm really interested
in volcanoes as analogs

13:48.542 --> 13:51.125
for deliberate intervention
into the climate system.

13:51.208 --> 13:53.291
It's climate control, right?

13:53.375 --> 13:56.458
It's changing the way the
global climate system works,

13:56.542 --> 13:59.333
to try and reduce
the worst impacts
of climate change.

13:59.417 --> 14:01.875
Smith:
Scientists are now studying

14:01.959 --> 14:05.125
how the deliberate introduction
of sulfur into the atmosphere

14:05.208 --> 14:08.500
