will be studied to better
understand volcanic aerosols

15:03.166 --> 15:06.041
and how to replicate
their cooling effect.

15:06.125 --> 15:07.375
Man:
The drone is about-- gonna be

15:07.458 --> 15:09.458
about the same
elevation as the top.

15:11.792 --> 15:13.125
-It's coming round.
-It is! Yeah.

15:14.917 --> 15:17.125
Man: Okay, we're coming
towards the top of
the clouds now. Over.

15:24.041 --> 15:27.834
Should be almost coming
over to you at this point. Over.

15:29.333 --> 15:32.375
Smith:
Geoengineering, using
volcanic-like particles,

15:32.458 --> 15:34.750
could successfully lower
the planet's temperatures,

15:34.834 --> 15:37.125
but it also carries
the serious potential

15:37.208 --> 15:39.792
for harming crop production
across the world.

15:41.166 --> 15:43.542
This stuff is so terrifying.

15:43.625 --> 15:46.542
It's such a big, scary idea.

15:46.625 --> 15:48.917
We have to be really honest

15:49.000 --> 15:50.750
about the pros
and cons of this stuff,

15:50.834 --> 15:54.166
because there are
nine billion lives
at stake, right?

15:55.166 --> 15:56.542
Smith:
In order to get
a better idea

15:56.625 --> 15:58.250
of the potentially
dangerous side effects

15:58.333 --> 15:59.792
of mimicking volcanoes,

15:59.875 --> 16:02.250
scientists are now
finalizing plans

16:02.333 --> 16:05.542
to spray sulfur particles
from a high-altitude balloon.

16:06.417 --> 16:08.333
What do you think
that the public's reaction?

16:08.417 --> 16:10.750
Because I just--
before you're even doing this,

16:10.834 --> 16:13.917
there's conspiracy theories
about chemtrails
and all of these things.

16:14.000 --> 16:17.458
We've examined all the
Twitter tweet-tweets ever,

16:17.542 --> 16:18.792
Uh, there's a way to do that.

16:18.875 --> 16:20.458
Most of the tweets that
have anything to do

16:20.542 --> 16:21.917
with geoengineering
are about chemtrails.

16:22.000 --> 16:23.750
-Wow!
-Yes!

16:23.834 --> 16:25.667
I mean, as a scientist,
I don't know what to react,
it's nuts.

16:25.750 --> 16:27.792
But as a citizen,
I worry about our ability

16:27.875 --> 16:30.166
to make any
sensible decisions

16:30.250 --> 16:31.917
if a significant fraction
of people believe stuff,

16:32.000 --> 16:34.458
which are just, kinda,
obviously false.

16:34.542 --> 16:36.834
To go back to the realm
of the sane.

16:36.917 --> 16:39.792
We've talked about
the solar reflection.

16:39.875 --> 16:43.000
Bring us-- Like, there's so much
carbon in the atmosphere,

16:43.083 --> 16:44.333
how do we even
make a dent?

16:44.417 --> 16:45.834
How do we scale that up?

16:45.917 --> 16:48.834
How do we-- how do we take
enough out to make it count?

16:48.917 --> 16:52.333
Removing all the carbon
from the atmosphere
is inherently hard

16:52.417 --> 16:54.834
'cause you actually have
to deal with all that material.

16:54.917 --> 16:56.667
I helped to form a start-up

16:56.750 --> 16:58.834
that has an
industrial technology
for removing CO2 from the air,

16:58.917 --> 17:01.000
and we have fought
like crazy

17:01.083 --> 17:03.166
to find industrially
scalable ways

17:03.250 --> 17:04.792
that are cheap to do that.

17:04.875 --> 17:08.542
Our market is capturing CO2
to combine it with hydrogen

17:08.625 --> 17:10.333
that comes from
cheap solar power

17:10.417 --> 17:11.709
to make transportation fuels--

17:11.792 --> 17:15.417
say to energize aircraft
in a carbon-neutral way.

17:16.417 --> 17:18.500
Smith:
Now, in a case
of tragic timing,

17:18.583 --> 17:22.291
just as we arrived to go
see this prototype plan
for carbon recapture,

17:22.375 --> 17:25.667
a state of emergency
had been declared
in British Columbia,

17:25.750 --> 17:29.041
with nearly 600 forest fires
raging out of control,

17:29.125 --> 17:32.792
thereby releasing
massive amounts of carbon
into the atmosphere.

17:37.166 --> 17:40.250
So this is our plant.
Great to have you here.

17:40.333 --> 17:42.208
-This land where
we're at here in Squamish...
-Yeah.

17:42.291 --> 17:44.208
...it's a great example of
climate change at work.

17:44.291 --> 17:45.875
This is a development site.

17:45.959 --> 17:47.375
We're building
lots of houses here
and industry.

17:47.458 --> 17:49.542
But they're having
to raise the land

17:49.625 --> 17:51.208
by about two meters,

17:51.291 --> 17:54.375
-because of the concern
about rising sea levels.
-Right.

17:54.458 --> 17:58.333
Meanwhile, we look around,
and we got 600 forest fires
in BC right now.

17:58.417 --> 18:00.417
So we can't see the mountains
because of the smoke.

18:02.417 --> 18:04.083
So all of this is smoke
from forest fires?

18:04.166 --> 18:05.667
Yeah. 600 in BC.

18:08.333 --> 18:10.542
Oldham:
Everything here
is a working mode,

18:10.625 --> 18:12.083
-full process working.
-Right.

18:12.166 --> 18:14.375
Think of it as, like,
a big cooling tower.

18:14.458 --> 18:17.750
Large fan, the fan
draws the CO2 in.

18:17.834 --> 18:20.291
Chemical reaction,
and we capture the CO.

18:20.375 --> 18:22.375
Wouldn't there be
more carbon to capture

18:22.458 --> 18:24.750
by dirty,
naughty factories?

18:24.834 --> 18:26.750
No, it's uniformly distributed.

18:26.834 --> 18:29.542
Yeah, so we could
put one of these plants
in the middle of Beijing,

18:29.625 --> 18:31.417
or we could
put it in the middle
of the Sahara Desert,

18:31.500 --> 18:34.041
you would capture
the same amount
of atmospheric CO2.

18:34.125 --> 18:36.291
So, we as a species,
have put it in,

18:36.375 --> 18:38.250
so we, as a species,
should be taking it out.

18:38.333 --> 18:39.917
Well, that's our choice,
but I think we have to,

18:40.000 --> 18:41.709
-or find somewhere
else to live.
-(chuckles): Right.

18:41.792 --> 18:45.875
And so, it's basically,
we recycle plastic,
we recycle paper,

18:45.959 --> 18:48.917
we recycle wood,
why don't we recycle energy?

18:49.000 --> 18:50.291
You're hitting the nail
on the head.

18:50.375 --> 18:52.625
We would like people
to be recycling their fuel

18:52.709 --> 18:55.291
in the same way as
they recycle other things.

18:55.375 --> 18:58.834
Smith: Your technology is,
we're gonna refine
that energy,

18:58.917 --> 19:01.083
that carbon out
of the atmosphere,

19:01.166 --> 19:03.750
combine it with
hydrogen and water,

19:03.834 --> 19:06.250
and then that's the same
as gas or jet fuel?

19:06.333 --> 19:09.083
Oldham:
Yeah. Yeah,
it's chemically the same.

19:09.166 --> 19:12.625
No pollutants.
So, for example, our diesel
burns completely clean.

19:12.709 --> 19:15.125
None of that black smoke
you see from trucks
when they go up hills.

19:15.208 --> 19:18.041
-Right.
-Completely clean, but yet,
it's chemically identical.

19:21.208 --> 19:22.417
Oldham:
Got a sample here.

19:22.500 --> 19:25.333
This is the world's first
recyclable fuel.

19:25.417 --> 19:26.667
And here's the
interesting thing.

19:26.750 --> 19:28.208
A carbon-neutral fuel
that's compatible

19:28.291 --> 19:30.041
with any vehicle
in the world today.

19:30.125 --> 19:31.166
Right.

19:31.250 --> 19:32.667
So that car
you just drove up in?

19:32.750 --> 19:34.792
-We can make that
carbon neutral tomorrow.
-Wow.

19:34.875 --> 19:36.166
Any vehicle,

19:36.250 --> 19:38.875
any performance vehicle,
any battered old truck,

19:38.959 --> 19:40.000
airplanes,

19:40.083 --> 19:41.291
we're compatible
with all of those.

19:41.375 --> 19:42.500
Which is significant,

19:42.583 --> 19:44.208
because nobody's
making electric tractors,

19:44.291 --> 19:45.542
-or electric planes.
-Right.

19:45.625 --> 19:47.458
Do you have to do
any modifications?

19:47.542 --> 19:48.875
-No.
-Wow!

19:48.959 --> 19:51.834
If we recycle all the plastic
out of the oceans,

19:51.917 --> 19:54.667
we'd never actually have
to produce anymore plastic

19:54.750 --> 19:57.500
because there's already
enough plastic out there
to continue anew.

19:57.583 --> 19:59.458
So there's enough carbon
in the atmosphere,

19:59.542 --> 20:01.208
that we could just
continually make...

20:01.291 --> 20:04.834
uh, uh,
synthetic fuel like this

20:04.917 --> 20:06.875
-to power our cars?
-Yes, you could.

20:06.959 --> 20:09.834
This is the real--
the killer app
for what we're doing.

20:09.917 --> 20:13.250
So transportation is about
20 percent of the CO2 emissions.

20:13.333 --> 20:15.041
How are we gonna
decarbonize that?

20:15.125 --> 20:17.333
There's a billion cars
in the world.

20:17.417 --> 20:20.041
So if we all go electric,

20:20.125 --> 20:21.875
$50,000 for an electric car,

20:21.959 --> 20:23.750
that's $50 trillion.

20:23.834 --> 20:27.333
Then you've got to deliver
energy and electricity
to each car.

20:27.417 --> 20:28.875
-It's a massive change.
-Yeah.

20:28.959 --> 20:31.917
Alternatively, why don't
we just change the fuel?

20:32.000 --> 20:34.625
The price to you at the pump
will be the same.

20:35.792 --> 20:37.375
Smith:
Cars powered by this fuel

20:37.458 --> 20:39.875
would still release some
carbon into the atmosphere,

20:39.959 --> 20:42.709
but at least they'd be
releasing recycled carbon

20:42.792 --> 20:44.875
that could be captured again.

20:44.959 --> 20:48.875
Having something like
a carbon-neutral gas
isn't even enough.

20:48.959 --> 20:50.667
We've got to start
going negative.

20:50.750 --> 20:54.375
We've got to
actually pull carbon
out of the atmosphere.

20:54.458 --> 20:57.709
Now, can-- can this do that,
and what's the plan there?

20:57.792 --> 21:00.709
Yeah, absolutely.
We can take the CO2
generated here,

21:00.792 --> 21:01.875
and bury that underground

21:01.959 --> 21:03.542
and you get to
negative emissions.

21:03.625 --> 21:05.917
-Right.
-It's a hugely important thing.

21:06.000 --> 21:08.583
And how many
do you need to scale it
to get to carbon negative?

21:08.667 --> 21:10.208
Oldham:
You need less of these

21:10.291 --> 21:12.875
than there are power stations
in the world today

21:12.959 --> 21:14.792
to net emissions out to zero.

21:14.875 --> 21:16.959
And how--
so how many is that?

21:17.041 --> 21:18.875
It's in the region
of tens of thousands.

21:18.959 --> 21:22.625
If we are taking measures
as we should be,
to move emissions elsewhere,

21:22.709 --> 21:25.959
now you start getting
to an overall negative
emissions for the world.

21:26.041 --> 21:29.208
Why isn't the world
rushing to Squamish, BC,

21:29.291 --> 21:32.583
and saying, "Can we please
make 100,000 of these?"

21:32.667 --> 21:35.417
-So, first of all, we're open
and ready to receive the world.
-Yeah.

21:35.500 --> 21:37.750
Um, secondly,
we've really just got

21:37.834 --> 21:40.500
to proof of concept here,
and it's working.

21:40.583 --> 21:43.333
So the next step of our business
is to expand across the globe...

21:43.417 --> 21:45.291
-Smith: Scale.
-...make carbon-neutral fuel,

21:45.375 --> 21:46.792
and when the scientists
and the governments

21:46.875 --> 21:49.458
decide that they need
to do negative emissions,

21:49.542 --> 21:51.166
the technology's ready.

21:52.208 --> 21:54.792
Smith:
Now, obviously creating
a carbon-neutral fuel

21:54.875 --> 21:57.792
made by refining it out of
pre-existing greenhouse gasses

21:57.875 --> 21:59.959
would be a positive first step,

22:00.041 --> 22:02.417
however there is so much
carbon in the atmosphere,

22:02.500 --> 22:04.625
that we need to get
to negative emissions,

22:04.709 --> 22:06.250
effectively going backwards,

22:06.333 --> 22:08.291
and reversing the
greenhouse effects

22:08.375 --> 22:10.166
and actually cooling down
the planet

22:10.250 --> 22:12.625
by removing more CO2
than we're adding

22:12.709 --> 22:16.834
and sequestering the
excess carbon underground.

22:16.917 --> 22:18.875
Now, while these
technologies are promising,

22:18.959 --> 22:21.000
and give us hope
for a brighter future,

22:21.083 --> 22:23.166
all human innovation, it seems,

22:23.250 --> 22:25.500
come with unintended
consequences.

22:25.583 --> 22:29.166
There could also
be a negative

22:29.250 --> 22:32.166
if countries weaponize,
or not even weaponize,

22:32.250 --> 22:33.625
but say, "You know what?

22:33.709 --> 22:35.542
"I need a little bit more,
or a little bit less rain.

22:35.625 --> 22:37.291
I'm gonna do this.
I'm gonna add that."

22:37.375 --> 22:40.458
Could this be
the new arms race?

22:40.542 --> 22:43.500
No technologies come without
the potential for misuse.

22:43.583 --> 22:46.333
So, I think there are
really two kinds of misuse
we're worried about.

22:46.417 --> 22:49.375
One is, sort of,
actual misuse in action.

22:49.458 --> 22:52.166
That is, some country
tries to make more rain
in one place,

22:52.250 --> 22:53.875
and that makes it
worse for somebody else.

22:53.959 --> 22:55.875
That's a realistic fear,
I think.

22:56.792 --> 22:58.709
Smith:
And weather
manipulation technology

22:58.792 --> 23:00.375
is already being tested.

23:00.458 --> 23:02.750
(firing)

23:02.834 --> 23:05.375
Newswoman:
China spends millions
of dollars every year

23:05.458 --> 23:08.250
on the world's largest
cloud-seeding program,

23:08.333 --> 23:11.125
using it frequently
to mitigate drought.

23:12.583 --> 23:14.166
Another form
of misuse is the--

23:14.250 --> 23:16.375
the misuse of these
being over-promoted

23:16.458 --> 23:18.542
and being used as a way
to weaken efforts

23:18.625 --> 23:20.834
to cut emissions
of carbon pollution,

23:20.917 --> 23:23.750
which we must cut
if we want to deal
with the climate crisis.

23:23.834 --> 23:25.208
This is our solution, then,

23:25.291 --> 23:27.041
and we can keep driving
all our cars and everything.

23:27.125 --> 23:28.542
Absolutely.

23:28.625 --> 23:30.166
Say, the big petrol states,

23:30.250 --> 23:33.208
or Exxon, or people who
want to push against

23:33.291 --> 23:35.709
the need to reduce
CO2 emissions,

23:35.792 --> 23:37.875
they will over-claim
how well this works

23:37.959 --> 23:39.375
and kind of
want to use it

23:39.458 --> 23:41.250
-as a "Get out
of Jail Free" card.
-Right.

23:41.333 --> 23:43.583
So they'll want to say, "Ah,
we don't need to worry now.

23:43.667 --> 23:45.083
"Just go back
and drive your SUVs

23:45.166 --> 23:46.458
"and fly as much as you like,

23:46.542 --> 23:48.041
and we don't need
to cut emissions."

23:49.333 --> 23:51.792
Smith:
Our failure to stop
greenhouse emissions

23:51.875 --> 23:54.542
after years of scientific
evidence and warnings

23:54.625 --> 23:57.208
has gotten us
to this dangerous place,

23:57.291 --> 24:00.083
and it is quickly becoming
the greatest threat
to our species

24:00.166 --> 24:01.875
The irony here is,

24:01.959 --> 24:05.041
that the scientists
most invested in
studying geoengineering,

24:05.125 --> 24:08.917
are the same ones
who are most afraid
of its consequences.

24:09.000 --> 24:12.417
Box:
We have started this era
of-- of geoengineering.

24:12.500 --> 24:13.458
It's just beginning.

24:13.542 --> 24:15.583
It's going to be a wild ride.

24:15.667 --> 24:18.041
I don't see us
backing away from it.

24:18.125 --> 24:20.750
It's the engineering project
of the century.

24:20.834 --> 24:24.083
Field:
There's this whole moral
hazard to geoengineering.

24:24.166 --> 24:25.500
If you have a solution,

24:25.583 --> 24:27.917
people say, "Great!
I don't have to change a thing."

24:28.000 --> 24:30.291
And that's not the message
that people should get.

24:30.375 --> 24:32.750
Smith:
I hope this
never has to be used,

24:32.834 --> 24:36.166
but if we get to a point
where we do have to use it,

24:36.250 --> 24:37.667
it's probably going to be...

24:37.750 --> 24:39.417
(Neukermans speaking)

24:39.500 --> 24:41.333
We should be thinking of this,
you know, as a war.

24:41.417 --> 24:42.834
Yeah.

24:44.125 --> 24:46.125
Oldham:
I think we need to be
reducing our emissions

24:46.208 --> 24:47.458
in multiple different areas.

24:47.542 --> 24:49.959
You can't rely on
one solution for everything.

24:50.041 --> 24:51.083
This is not a panacea.

24:51.166 --> 24:53.417
We would be
foolish as a species

24:53.500 --> 24:56.083
to rely on
just one technology
or just one solution.

24:56.166 --> 24:58.834
We need multiple solutions.
It's a huge problem.

24:58.917 --> 25:00.458
Watson:
Worst case scenario,

25:00.542 --> 25:02.625
it might be the dumbest
thing we ever do.

25:02.709 --> 25:04.166
It's a very odd situation
to work on something

25:04.250 --> 25:07.125
that you really hope
never happens.

25:07.208 --> 25:11.166
Were we ever to actually
deploy solar geoengineering
full-scale,

25:11.250 --> 25:14.208
it's the clearest indication
that we failed.

25:14.291 --> 25:17.000
It's a desperate act,
make no bones about it.

25:17.083 --> 25:19.166
If there's a way
not to do this,

25:19.250 --> 25:22.667
every academic
that's working on it
will rejoice.

